        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down.</placeName>
                    <date>23<hi rend="superscript">d</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Romanes</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>I am very glad about the microscope.— H. Spencers plan w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. have quite destroyed the graciosity of the little present.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I am better, but am no great shakes &amp; weak enough.—</p>
<p>Ever yours sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p>
                    <p>I hope that you will be able soon to read the Sugar Cane paper.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The month and year are established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13600.xml">letter to G. J. Romanes, 6 January 1882</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD and Romanes had agreed to give <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_81.xml">Grant Allen</ref> a microscope, but were deliberating about when to present the gift (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13627.xml">letter to G. J. Romanes, 20 January 1882</ref>). No correspondence mentioning <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4495.xml">Herbert Spencer</ref> in connection with the matter has been found.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13600.xml">letter to G. J. Romanes, 6 January 1882</ref> and n. 1.</note>
            
        </div>
    
